ğŸ”¹ 2. Add Dependencies to pom.xml

<dependencies>
    <!-- Cucumber -->
    <dependency>
        <groupId>io.cucumber</groupId>
        <artifactId>cucumber-java</artifactId>
        <version>7.11.2</version>
    </dependency>

    <dependency>
        <groupId>io.cucumber</groupId>
        <artifactId>cucumber-junit</artifactId>
        <version>7.11.2</version>
    </dependency>

    <!-- Allure Cucumber Integration -->
    <dependency>
        <groupId>io.qameta.allure</groupId>
        <artifactId>allure-cucumber7-jvm</artifactId>
        <version>2.21.0</version>
    </dependency>

    <!-- JUnit -->
    <dependency>
        <groupId>junit</groupId>
        <artifactId>junit</artifactId>
        <version>4.13.2</version>
        <scope>test</scope>
    </dependency>
</dependencies>

<build>
    <plugins>
        <!-- Allure Maven Plugin -->
        <plugin>
            <groupId>io.qameta.allure</groupId>
            <artifactId>allure-maven</artifactId>
            <version>2.11.2</version>
        </plugin>
    </plugins>
</build>
ğŸ”¹ 3. Sample Feature File â€” login.feature

Feature: Login Feature

  Scenario: Successful login
    Given user navigates to login page
    When user enters valid username and password
    Then user is redirected to dashboard
ğŸ”¹ 4. Step Definitions â€” LoginSteps.java

package steps;

import io.cucumber.java.en.*;
import io.qameta.allure.Step;

public class LoginSteps {

    @Given("user navigates to login page")
    @Step("Navigate to Login Page")
    public void navigateToLoginPage() {
        System.out.println("Navigating to login page...");
    }

    @When("user enters valid username and password")
    @Step("Enter valid username and password")
    public void enterCredentials() {
        System.out.println("Entering credentials...");
    }

    @Then("user is redirected to dashboard")
    @Step("Verify dashboard redirection")
    public void verifyDashboard() {
        System.out.println("Redirected to dashboard...");
    }
}
ğŸ”¹ 5. Test Runner â€” TestRunner.java

package runners;

import org.junit.runner.RunWith;
import io.cucumber.junit.Cucumber;
import io.cucumber.junit.CucumberOptions;

@RunWith(Cucumber.class)
@CucumberOptions(
    features = "src/test/resources/features",
    glue = "steps",
    plugin = {
        "pretty",
        "io.qameta.allure.cucumber7jvm.AllureCucumber7Jvm"
    },
    monochrome = true
)
public class TestRunner {}
â–¶ï¸ How to Run and Generate Allure Report
ğŸ§ª Step 1: Run the Tests

mvn clean test
This will generate Allure raw report files in target/allure-results/.

ğŸ§¾ Step 2: Serve Allure Report Locally
Install Allure commandline tool (only once):


# Mac
brew install allure

# Windows (use Scoop or Chocolatey)
choco install allure
Then generate and open the report:


allure serve target/allure-results
This will open a rich HTML report in the browser.

ğŸ“Š What You Get in Allure Report
Feature â†’ Scenario â†’ Step structure

Timeline, History, Graphs
Attachments (screenshots, logs, etc.)
Failed step highlights
Trend & flaky test detection

ğŸ§© (Optional) Add Screenshots to Allure Report
Add a screenshot attachment in your step definition:

@Attachment(value = "Screenshot", type = "image/png")
public byte[] saveScreenshot(byte[] screenShot) {
    return screenShot;
}
If you're using Selenium + WebDriver, you can attach it directly like this:

@Attachment(value = "Screenshot", type = "image/png")
public byte[] takeScreenshot() {
    return ((TakesScreenshot) driver).getScreenshotAs(OutputType.BYTES);
}
